{"title_page": "Kelley Stand Road", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=April 2020}}\n'''Kelley Stand Road''' is an unpaved road running between [[Arlington, Vermont|East Arlington]] and [[Stratton, Vermont]], in southern Vermont. It travels over a high plateau adjacent to the [[Lye Brook Wilderness]] in the [[Green Mountain National Forest]] (GMNF). The road originally served numerous logging camps and early settlements during the nineteenth century. From Stratton, the road continues eastward to [[West Wardsboro, Vermont|West Wardsboro]] as a paved, year-round road. The western portion is dirt and not plowed or maintained during winter months. \n\n==History==\nKelley Stand Road is notable as the site of [[Daniel Webster]]'s famous Kelley Stand speech of July 1840; a historic marker commemorates the spot.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://dailygazette.com/article/2009/08/30/0830_webster |title=Orator Daniel Webster drew 15,000 to Vermont in 1840 |first=Bill |last=Buell |website=[[The Daily Gazette]] |date=August 30, 2009 |accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref> The road is near the location near where [[Benton MacKaye]] first conceived his idea of a hiking trail that ran along the [[Appalachian Mountains|Appalachian Mountain range]] of the eastern United States.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://archive.boston.com/travel/explorene/vermont/articles/2010/10/24/this_bit_of_the_long_trail_is_nothing_short_of_a_challenge/ |title=This bit of the Long Trail is nothing short of a challenge |first=Aubin |last=Tyler |newspaper=[[The Boston Globe]] |via=[[Boston.com]] |date=October 24, 2010 |accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Appalachian Trail and Long Trail==\n\nThe [[Appalachian Trail]] (AT), and likewise the [[Long Trail]] (LT), which share the same path in the southern Green Mountains of Vermont, cross Kelley Stand Road before the trail crosses over the summit of [[Stratton Mountain (Vermont)|Stratton Mountain]], which lies to the north of the road.  Overnight AT/LT trailhead parking is available on the road, which also serves as an access point for other nearby trails.\n\nNorthbound from Kelley Stand Road the next AT/LT shelter is the [[Stratton Pond (Vermont)|Stratton Pond]] shelter at AT mile point 1625, and to the south lies the Story Spring AT/LT shelter at mile point 1615.\n\n==Damage from Tropical Storm Irene==\nOn August 28, 2011, [[Tropical Storm Irene (2011)|Tropical Storm Irene]] caused major damage to the road. Until scheduled repairs were made by the [[US Forest Service]], it remained inaccessible from the Arlington side. Destinations could still be reached from the Stratton side. In September 2014, Kelley Stand Road was completely reopened from the Arlington side, after three years of reconstruction costing $3.8 million.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.benningtonbanner.com/stories/kelley-stand-road-officially-reopens,315809 |title=Kelley Stand Road officially reopens |first=Keith |last=Whitcomb Jr. |website=[[Bennington Banner]] |date=September 17, 2014 |accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070611173452/http://www.thisisvermont.com/storyarlistory.html Arlington, Vermont]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070607115705/http://www.appalachiantrail.org/site/c.jkLXJ8MQKtH/b.786749/k.D5F9/History.htm History of the Appalachian Trail]\n* [http://tnlandforms.us/at/ Appalachian Trail Shelters]\n\n[[Category:Roads in Vermont]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=April 2020}}\n'''Kelley Stand Road''' is an unpaved road running between [[Arlington, Vermont|East Arlington]] and [[Stratton, Vermont]], in southern Vermont. It travels over a high plateau adjacent to the [[Lye Brook Wilderness]] in the [[Green Mountain National Forest]] (GMNF). The road originally served numerous logging camps and early settlements during the nineteenth century. From Stratton, the road continues eastward to [[West Wardsboro, Vermont|West Wardsboro]] as a paved, year-round road. The western portion is dirt and not plowed or maintained during winter months. \n\n==History==\nKelley Stand Road is notable as the site of [[Daniel Webster]]'s famous Kelley Stand speech of July 1840; a historic marker commemorates the spot.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://dailygazette.com/article/2009/08/30/0830_webster |title=Orator Daniel Webster drew 15,000 to Vermont in 1840 |first=Bill |last=Buell |website=[[The Daily Gazette]] |date=August 30, 2009 |accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref> The road is near the location near where [[Benton MacKaye]] first conceived his idea of a hiking trail that ran along the [[Appalachian Mountains|Appalachian Mountain range]] of the eastern United States.\n\n==Appalachian Trail and Long Trail==\n\nThe [[Appalachian Trail]] (AT), and likewise the [[Long Trail]] (LT), which share the same path in the southern Green Mountains of Vermont, cross Kelley Stand Road before the trail crosses over the summit of [[Stratton Mountain (Vermont)|Stratton Mountain]], which lies to the north of the road.  Overnight AT/LT trailhead parking is available on the road, which also serves as an access point for other nearby trails.\n\nNorthbound from Kelley Stand Road the next AT/LT shelter is the [[Stratton Pond (Vermont)|Stratton Pond]] shelter at AT mile point 1625, and to the south lies the Story Spring AT/LT shelter at mile point 1615.\n\n==Damage from Tropical Storm Irene==\nOn August 28, 2011, [[Tropical Storm Irene (2011)|Tropical Storm Irene]] caused major damage to the road. Until scheduled repairs were made by the [[US Forest Service]], it remained inaccessible from the Arlington side. Destinations could still be reached from the Stratton side. In September 2014, Kelley Stand Road was completely reopened from the Arlington side, after three years of reconstruction costing $3.8 million.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.benningtonbanner.com/stories/kelley-stand-road-officially-reopens,315809 |title=Kelley Stand Road officially reopens |first=Keith |last=Whitcomb Jr. |website=[[Bennington Banner]] |date=September 17, 2014 |accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070611173452/http://www.thisisvermont.com/storyarlistory.html Arlington, Vermont]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070607115705/http://www.appalachiantrail.org/site/c.jkLXJ8MQKtH/b.786749/k.D5F9/History.htm History of the Appalachian Trail]\n* [http://tnlandforms.us/at/ Appalachian Trail Shelters]\n\n[[Category:Roads in Vermont]]\n", "name_user": "Dmoore5556", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:citation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kelley_Stand_Road"}
